03787nam a22005295i 9780520924581DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19981998cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209245817 a10.1525/97805209245812doi  a(DE-B1597)649089  a(OCoLC)1419789165  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aBIO0040002bisacsh1 aFrigyesi, Judit, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBela Bartok and Turn-of-the-Century Budapest /cJudit Frigyesi; ed. by Judit Frigyesi. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1998] 4c©1998  a1 online resource (367 p.) :b10 b/w photographs, 48 music examples  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPART I History and Aesthetics -- tPART 2 Poetry and Music -- tAfterword -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBartók's music is greatly prized by concertgoers, yet we know little about the intellectual milieu that gave rise to his artistry. Bartók is often seen as a lonely genius emerging from a gray background of an "underdeveloped country." Now Judit Frigyesi offers a broader perspective on Bartók's art by grounding it in the social and cultural life of turn-of-the-century Hungary and the intense creativity of its modernist movement. Bartók spent most of his life in Budapest, an exceptional man living in a remarkable milieu. Frigyesi argues that Hungarian modernism in general and Bartók's aesthetic in particular should be understood in terms of a collective search for wholeness in life and art and for a definition of identity in a rapidly changing world. Is it still possible, Bartók's generation of artists asked, to create coherent art in a world that is no longer whole? Bartók and others were preoccupied with this question and developed their aesthetics in response to it. In a discussion of Bartók and of Endre Ady, the most influential Hungarian poet of the time, Frigyesi demonstrates how different branches of art and different personalities responded to the same set of problems, creating oeuvres that appear as reflections of one another. She also examines Bartók's Bluebeard's Castle, exploring philosophical and poetic ideas of Hungarian modernism and linking Bartók's stylistic innovations to these concepts.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aMusic. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Composers & Musicians.2bisacsh1 aFrigyesi, Judit, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052022254040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092458140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520924581423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520924581/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles